  "text": "Secondary PAP with hematological disease and without autoimmune mechanisms is common, but autoimmune PAP with hematological disease, as in the present case, has rarely been reported. Previous case reports of PAP with MPN are listed in Table ( [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . As noted in other reports (9), CML and MDS are the most common cause of PAP, and there are no reports of PAP with MPN U such as ours. In one case of PAP, GM-CSF autoantibodies were detected, and it was speculated that ABL tyrosine kinase inhibitor-induced mechanisms were involved [CITATION_5] . Interestingly, three out of four cases listed in Table were diagnosed with PAP when MPN progressed or disseminated infection occurred. In the remaining case, MPN improved temporarily when wholelung lavage was provided as treatment for PAP. However, in our case, the relationship between the clinical course of MPN and PAP was not apparent.",
